Class Employee

  • java.lang.Object
    • domain.Employee
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Comparable<Employee>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    SalesEmployee

    public class Employee
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Comparable<Employee>
    A class representing an Employee.
    Usage example: 
     Employee myEmployee = new Employee("Christopher", "Hield", 5000, 50.0, new int[]{5, 6, 7, 8, 9});
 Employee myEmployee = new Employee(Employee otherEmployee);
    Since:
    Version 1.8
    Author:
    Christopher Hield
    See Also:
    Department, SalesEmployee, Timecard

                java.lang.String lName,
                int eId,
                double hRate,
                int[] daysIn)
         throws utils.NullParameterException,
                utils.BadParameterException
        Constructor for the Employee class - need non-null and non-empty First and Last name, an Employee ID between 1000 and 9999, a higher than zero Hourly Rate, and an int Array holding the worked days.
        Parameters:
        fName - The Employee's first name
        lName - The Employee's last name
        eId - The Employee's ID
        hRate - The Employee's Hourly Rate
        daysIn - The Employee's int Array with the worked days
        Throws:
        utils.NullParameterException - If either First name or Last name parameters are Null
        utils.BadParameterException - If either First name or Last name have are longer than 20 characters. If ID is not between 1000 and 9999. If Hourly Rate is less or equal to zero
        See Also:
        Employee(Employee)

        public int compareTo(Employee eIn)

        Specified by:
        compareTo in interface java.lang.Comparable<Employee>
        Returns:
        Returns -1 if ID number of passed Employee is larger. Returns 0 if they have the same ID. Returns 1 if ID number of passed Employee is smaller.
